$1(a){return this.a.GW('**What It Measures**\nDetects when the same speaker repeats concepts, phrases, or questions multiple times during a conversation.\n\n**Why It Matters**\nRepetitive speech is a well-documented marker of memory difficulties. People with cognitive decline often:\n\u2022 Ask the same questions repeatedly\n\u2022 Retell the same stories without realizing\n\u2022 Circle back to concepts they\'ve already discussed\n\n**How It Works**\n1. **Text Extraction**: Each speech segment is analyzed for noun phrases (concepts) and complete sentences (especially questions)\n\n2. **Similarity Matching**: Uses SequenceMatcher algorithm to compare phrases\n   - Threshold determines how similar two phrases must be (default 85%)\n   - Lower threshold = more matches, possibly false positives\n   - Higher threshold = stricter, may miss paraphrased repetitions\n\n3. **Same-Speaker Filter**: Only counts when the SAME person repeats themselves\n   - Normal conversational echoing between speakers is ignored\n   - This is critical for accurate dementia screening\n\n4. **Gap Requirement**: Repetitions must be separated by a minimum number of segments\n   - Filters out immediate self-corrections ("I went to the... the store")\n   - Default: 2 segments apart\n\n**Research Basis**\nPMID 29493412 - "Repetitive speech phenomena in primary progressive aphasia"\n\n**Adjusting Sensitivity**\n\u2022 **More sensitive**: Lower threshold (70-80%), gap of 1\n\u2022 **Less sensitive**: Higher threshold (90%+), gap of 3+\n',B.fZ,B.c_,"Repetition Detection")},
